By: Delegate Lewis
Introduced and read first time: February 11, 2026
Assigned to: Ways and Means
Committee Report: Favorable
House action: Adopted
Read second time: March 2, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Judicial In Rem Tax Foreclosure – Notice Requirements
3 FOR the purpose of altering requirements for providing notice to interested parties when a
4 county or municipal corporation files a complaint for a judicial in rem foreclosure on
5 certain vacant and abandoned property; and generally relating to judicial in rem tax
6 foreclosure.
7 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
8 Article – Tax – Property
9 Section 14–875
10 Annotated Code of Maryland
11 (2019 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
12 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
13 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
14 Article – Tax – Property
15 14–875.
16 (a) A county or municipal corporation may file a complaint for an in rem
17 foreclosure action in accordance with this part.
18 (b) The county or municipal corporation may not file a complaint for an in rem
19 foreclosure action unless:
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb1110*

2 HOUSE BILL 1110
1 (1) the tax on the real property has been delinquent for at least 6 months;
2 and
3 (2) the right to appeal the notice of the property as vacant and unsafe or
4 unfit has tolled.
5 (c) All taxes shall:
6 (1) be included in the foreclosure action; and
7 (2) cease to be a lien against the real property if a judgment is entered
8 foreclosing the existing interests of all interested parties in the real property.
9 (d) The county or municipal corporation shall:
10 (1) file the complaint for an in rem foreclosure in the circuit court of the
11 county where the real property is located; and
12 (2) [within 5 days after filing the complaint, send notice and a copy of the
13 complaint to each interested party by first–class mail and certified mail, postage prepaid,
14 return receipt requested, bearing a postmark from the United States Postal Service]
15 SERVE THE COMPLAINT ON EACH INTERESTED PARTY IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE
16 MARYLAND RULES.
17 (e) The complaint for an in rem foreclosure shall include:
18 (1) the identity of the county or municipal corporation on behalf of which
19 the complaint is filed;
20 (2) the name and address of the county or municipal corporation;
21 (3) a description of the real property as it appears in the county land
22 records;
23 (4) the tax identification number of the real property;
24 (5) a statement that the taxes are delinquent at the time of the filing;
25 (6) the amount of taxes that are delinquent as of the date of filing;
26 (7) the names and last known addresses of all interested parties in the real
27 property and, if applicable, a statement that the address of a particular interested party in
28 the real property is unknown;

HOUSE BILL 1110 3
1 (8) a statement that the real property is a vacant lot or improved property
2 cited as vacant and unsafe or unfit for habitation or other authorized use on a housing or
3 building violation notice;
4 (9) copies of any violation notice cited under paragraph (8) of this
5 subsection;
6 (10) a request that the circuit court not schedule a hearing on the complaint
7 until 30 days after the date that the complaint is filed; and
8 (11) a request that the circuit court enter a judgment that forecloses the
9 existing interests of all interested parties in the real property and orders ownership of the
10 real property to be transferred to the county or municipal corporation.
11 (f) A complaint for an in rem foreclosure may be amended to include all taxes
12 that become delinquent after the commencement of the in rem foreclosure action.
13 (g) (1) Subject to paragraph (2) of this subsection, an interested party has the
14 right to cure the delinquent taxes and liens on the real property by paying all past due fees,
15 payments, and penalties at any time before the entry of the foreclosure judgment.
16 (2) The right to cure the delinquent taxes and liens on the real property
17 extinguishes once the foreclosure judgment is entered.
18 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
19 1, 2026.
Approved:
